<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="test-tdd-red-green-split-agents">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>sdlc-ai</group>
    <domain>sdlc-ai</domain>
    <summary>Split TDD into RED and GREEN sub-agents with disjoint tool permissions so neither can cheat; orchestrator asserts a real failing-to-passing transition before merging.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>tdd</tag>
      <tag>red-green</tag>
      <tag>sub-agents</tag>
      <tag>tool-permissions</tag>
      <tag>sdlc-ai</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>test</category>
    <difficulty>advanced</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-30</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>TDD with Red and Green in Separate Agents</title>
    <summary>When an AI coding agent runs the TDD loop, the test-writer (RED) and the implementer (GREEN) must execute in separate sub-agents with non-overlapping tool permissions: RED can write to `tests/` and read sources but cannot edit them; GREEN can edit sources and read the failing test output but cannot modify the test file. The orchestrator passes only the acceptance criterion to RED, only the test diff and pytest/jest failure to GREEN, and asserts a real RED→GREEN transition before merging. Without the split, a single agent that owns both files cheats by editing the test to pass.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Single-context TDD with an LLM degenerates into "edit the test until both pass" because the model has zero accountability for which file it changed. Separating the loop into sub-agents with disjoint tool permissions enforces the discipline mechanically: RED literally cannot edit `src/`, GREEN literally cannot edit `tests/`. This is the same separation-of-concerns argument that made TDD work for humans (writing tests first concentrates the mind) — re-applied at the tool-permission layer the agent is fine-tuned to respect. Reports from production Claude Code skill setups (alexop.dev, simonwillison.net) describe consistent convergence behavior under this split that single-context TDD never achieves.</p>
      <p>The orchestrator drives one cycle per acceptance criterion: AC → RED-subagent emits failing test, runner confirms RED, GREEN-subagent edits source until runner confirms green, refactor-subagent (optional, with both directories read-only) reviews the diff. If RED ever produces a passing test, the cycle aborts — passing tests on the first try mean the spec was already satisfied or the test is wrong.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Agent-driven feature work whose spec is testable in pure functions or HTTP responses (parsers, validators, calculators, API endpoints).</item>
        <item>Bug-fix tickets with a clear regression scenario — RED reproduces, GREEN fixes.</item>
        <item>Greenfield modules where the public API surface is known up front.</item>
        <item>Hard-spec migrations (port library X to language Y) — golden-master tests fit the same split.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Pure UI styling, layout work, exploratory spikes — TDD overhead is wasted there.</item>
        <item>Tasks whose acceptance criterion is not testable (research notes, prose docs, design artifacts).</item>
        <item>Throwaway scripts and demo code.</item>
        <item>Refactors of code that already has full test coverage — the existing tests are the RED of choice; no new test cycle needed.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="tool-permission-split">
      <p>An agent fine-tuned on `allowed_tools` will respect the list. Splitting RED and GREEN into two skill files with disjoint tool sets converts "TDD discipline" from a guideline into a precondition the orchestrator can verify.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>The RED sub-agent skill frontmatter MUST list only `Read` and `Write` (no `Edit`), and Write MUST be path-restricted to `tests/`. The GREEN sub-agent skill frontmatter MUST list only `Read` and `Edit` (no `Write`), and Edit MUST be path-restricted to `src/`. Neither skill may include `Bash` for file moves. Any deviation fails the gate and the cycle aborts.</statement>
        <rationale>Tool-permission discipline is the only mechanism that prevents a single LLM context from "fixing" a failing test by mutating it; trust-based prompts ("please do not edit the test file") fail under sufficiently long sessions.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
# .claude/skills/tdd-red.md frontmatter
description: "Write the smallest failing test for the AC."
allowed_tools: [Read, Write]
write_paths: ["tests/**"]
      ]]></code>
        <note>RED cannot edit `src/` even if it tries.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad">
        <code lang="yaml"><![CDATA[
description: "Write a failing test, then make it pass."
allowed_tools: [Read, Write, Edit, Bash]
      ]]></code>
        <note>Single agent owns both directories; will edit the test to pass.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>RED skill includes `Edit` "just in case it needs to fix a typo in an existing test."</description>
        <reason>That escape hatch reopens the cheating path; a typo fix belongs in a separate refactor cycle, not inside a RED turn.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="orchestrator-contract">
      <p>RED hands off only the new test file path; GREEN never sees the spec. The orchestrator is the only component that runs the test runner and is therefore the only component that knows whether the build is red or green.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Between RED and GREEN turns the orchestrator MUST: (1) run the project's test command on the new test, (2) require exit code != 0, (3) abort and surface "first-try-pass" if exit code == 0, (4) pass to GREEN ONLY the failing test diff and the runner's failure stanza — never the original AC, never the test source. After GREEN, the orchestrator re-runs the same command and refuses to commit unless exit code == 0.</statement>
        <rationale>A passing first-run test means either the feature already exists or the test does not exercise the spec; either case is a hard signal to halt rather than continue. Keeping the AC out of GREEN's prompt prevents AC paraphrasing from leaking implementation hints back into the test.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
ORCHESTRATOR LOG:
  RED   -> wrote tests/test_refund.py::test_refund_within_14_days
  RUN   -> pytest -q  -> 1 failed (AssertionError)
  GREEN -> edited src/refund.py
  RUN   -> pytest -q  -> 1 passed
  COMMIT
      ]]></code>
        <note>Real RED, then real GREEN, both confirmed by the runner.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="bad">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
ORCHESTRATOR LOG:
  RED   -> wrote tests/test_refund.py::test_refund_within_14_days
  RUN   -> pytest -q  -> 1 passed   (!!)
  GREEN -> (skipped, already green)
  COMMIT
      ]]></code>
        <note>First-try-pass committed; the test is almost certainly tautological.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Orchestrator passes the original acceptance criterion to GREEN "for context."</description>
        <reason>GREEN should derive intent from the failing test alone; reintroducing the AC lets the model satisfy the AC text without making the test pass.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/tdd-red.skill.md" purpose="Frontmatter for the RED sub-agent skill (Read + Write on tests/ only)."/>
      <template path="templates/tdd-green.skill.md" purpose="Frontmatter for the GREEN sub-agent skill (Read + Edit on src/ only)."/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://alexop.dev/posts/custom-tdd-workflow-claude-code-vue/"/>
      <link href="https://simonwillison.net/guides/agentic-engineering-patterns/red-green-tdd/"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
